<DOC><DOCNO> AP890306-0162 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-03-06-89 1845EST</FILEID><FIRST>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     03-06 0589</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0603</SECOND><HEAD>Widespread Snow In East, With Flooding In Appalachians</HEAD><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   A strong weather system spread heavy snow from the Plains oversections of the Ohio Valley, and heavy rain caused flooding in theAppalachians.   Snowfall ended over Missouri after more than a foot fell in someareas. Lebanon got 16 inches and 15 inches fell ar Marshfield. The11 inches at St. Louis was the 11th heaviest snowfall on record, andthe fourth heaviest for March, the National Weather Service said.   In Arkansas, snow and ice accumulations piled up 12 to 14 inchesdeep in Benton County and 8 to 12 inches in Washington County.   In central and southern Illinois, 6 to 8 inches fell atTaylorville and Litchfield, with 6 inches in Moultrie county.Northern Indiana got 2 to 4 inches.   Freezing rain and sleet mixed with the snow from southernIllinois to southern Indiana and Ohio. A layer of ice three-quartersof an inch thick accumulated on trees at Clay City, Ill. In southernOhio, ice on electrical lines caused scattered power outages.   Snow also fell on southern Pennsylvania, sections of New Jerseyand southeastern New York.   A mixture of rain and sleet fell just south of the snow area.   A line of strong showers and thunderstorms developed over westernsections of the Carolinas. Near Mooresville, N.C., intensethunderstorms damaged several homes, overturned cars and blew downfences.   Heavy rain that fell over much of the Ohio and Tennessee valleysduring the last couple days caused rivers to rise in Kentucky, WestVirginia, Tennessee and Ohio. West Virginia had flash flooding, andmany northern streams were expected to crest above flood stageduring the night. The Kentucky River was rising at a rate of a footand a half an hour in many areas and was expected to crest duringthe evening over eastern Kentucky.   In Tennessee, roads were flooded in Grundy and Marion counties.   Light lake-effect snow fell along the western shores of LakeMichigan in northern Wisconsin.   Light rain and fog spread along the northern and central PacificCoast.   Record lows were reported Monday at Austin, Texas, 27;Bryan-College Station, Texas, 29; Corpus Christi, Texas, 29; FortWorth, Texas, 20; Galveston, Texas, 27; Grand Island, Neb., 10 belowzero; Houston, 25; Huron, S.D., 17 below; Lake Charles, La., 25;Midland, Texas, 15; Port Arthur, Texas, 24; Shreveport, La., 24;Victoria, Texas; and Wichita Falls, Texas, 8.   Temperatures around the nation at 2 p.m. EST ranged from 9degrees at Limestone, Maine, to 85 at Fort Myers, Fla. Monday's lowfor the Lower 48 states was 18 degrees below zero at Ord, Neb.   Tuesday's forecast called for showers over Virginia and theCarolinas, the Tennessee Valley and the lower half of the FloridaPeninsula; widespread rain along the northern and central PacificCoast and the northern and central Intermountain region between theSierra Nevada and the Rockies; and snow from southern Pennsylvaniato New Jersey and the southern New England coast.   Highs in the teens and 20s were predicted from the upper GreatLakes to northern sections of the Ohio Valley, the lower Great Lakesand New England; in the 30s and 40s from Washington state to thenorthern Rockies, the northern and central Plains, Oklahoma, easternTexas, much of the Mississippi Valley, the Tennessee Valley and themiddle Atlantic Coast; in the 70s over the southern FloridaPeninsula; in the 70s and 80s over Southern California; andgenerally in the 50s and 60s over the rest of the nation.</TEXT></DOC>